# Subagent and Skill Routing

Use the best specialized helper when scope or risk justifies it.

## 1) Required Subagent Triggers

Use subagents proactively in these cases:

- **Broad codebase exploration:** use `explore` for architecture discovery, multi-area searches, or ownership mapping.
- **Pre-implementation planning review:** apply the `plan-engine-change` skill first; then use `engine-planning` when the plan is large, ambiguous, high-risk, or needs an architecture-aware pressure test before implementation.
- **Post-change validation:** run `test-runner` after behavior-changing edits and report outcomes.
- **Completion verification:** run `verifier` for non-trivial implementations before final handoff.
- **Doc/architecture alignment:** run `architecture-and-docs` after behavior changes that affect contracts or docs.
- **Contract and naming refactors:** run `migration-and-terminology` when replacing fields/types/APIs/terms or removing stale compatibility guidance.
- **Plugin/system wiring:** run `plugin-and-systems` for `ToolPlugin`/`EditorPlugin` work and registry/event-bus integration.
- **Component schema work:** run `ecs-and-components` when adding/changing ComponentDef data/properties/registration.

## 2) Skill Usage Rule

Before implementing scaffold-like work, check for a matching project skill and use it first.

- Node/behavior graph additions -> `scaffold-behavior-node`
- ECS component additions -> `scaffold-ecs-component`
- Tool plugin additions -> `scaffold-tool-plugin`
- Editor plugin/system additions -> `scaffold-editor-plugin`
- Worker/off-thread simulation scaffolding -> `scaffold-simulation-worker`
- Blender prop/character scaffolding -> `scaffold-blender-prop`, `scaffold-blender-character`
- 2D spritesheet NPC authoring (`public/sprites`, `sprite-manifest.json`) -> `scaffold-sprite-character`
- Engine-aware planning / Cursor plan flow -> `plan-engine-change`
- Cursor rule creation/maintenance -> `create-rule`
- Cursor skill authoring -> `create-skill`

## 3) Parallelization Policy

- If multiple independent investigations are needed, launch subagents in parallel (up to safe limit).
- Do not delegate simple single-file needle queries to subagents; use direct file/search tools instead.

## 4) Background Execution Policy

Default to foreground unless task runtime is long and non-blocking.

- Prefer background for `test-runner` when running broad/full test passes.
- Prefer background for `verifier` when verification scope spans many files/systems.
- Prefer background for `architecture-and-docs` for broad consistency audits.
- Prefer background for long `explore` sweeps across multiple domains.
- Keep foreground for short checks or outputs that immediately gate next edits.
- Background runs must be polled and summarized before final handoff.

## 5) Done Criteria

- Chosen helper path is explicit in execution (subagent and/or skill used when trigger matched).
- If no trigger matched, proceed directly and keep work concise.

## 6) Studio-style agents and skills (optional depth)

Use when the task matches a **department** role from `.cursor/docs/studio/agent-coordination-map.md`:

- Vision, pillars, cross-discipline conflict -> `creative-director` or `technical-director` (conceptual review, not implementation ownership).
- Scheduling, milestones, release process -> `producer`, `release-manager`, `qa-lead` as appropriate.
- Gameplay feature implementation in `src/systems/**` -> `gameplay-programmer` / `systems-designer`; rendering -> `voxel-engine-specialist`; workers/WASM -> `web-worker-wasm-specialist`; plugins -> `editor-plugin-specialist` or existing `plugin-and-systems`.
- Studio workflow skills live under `.cursor/skills/` (`start`, `sprint-plan`, `code-review`, `brainstorm`, etc.). Prefer project engine skills (`plan-engine-change`, scaffolds) when tasks overlap.
